Collector: Dosmann, Michael; Schwartz Sax, Miles; Hata, Yoshinari; Aizawa, Mineaki
Habitat: Stream edge in mesic forest dominated by an overstory of Ulmus davidiana var. japonica and Alnus japonica, and Pachysandra terminalis below.
Soil: High organic matter; reddish silt where wild boars had upturned the soil.
Description: Growing in quarter- to half-shade. A few patches found. Large shrubs to small trees, multi-stemmed and spreading. Height typically to 4 m; Spread 4 to 5 m. Bark light brown to tan. Leaves typical for species, large and leathery, less herbivory compared to nearby V. plicatum. Bright red, ovoid drupes almost 1 cm long.
Collection Miscellaneous: Seed collected from 3 trees. Japanese name means "sesame tree/shrub" due to smell of crushed leaves.
Associated Taxa: Aesculus turbinata, Cimicifuga simplex, Ilex crenata, Pachysandra terminalis, Smilax sp., Symplocos paniculata, Ulmus davidiana var. japonica, Viburnum plicatum

Fruiting is occurring where increased sunlight is available; however, most plants appear to be middle understory in this habitat.

Description: This species is a deciduous shrub with clear stems to about 1-2 meters and a spreading, irregularly rounded crown. Plants range from 3-4.5 meters tall x 3-4 meters wide. Habitat: Wooded cliff above sandy beach and high tide line in a protected cover.
Description: Spreading, multistemmed shrub anchored into rocks and sand. Growing in 75 to 50% shade. Height 3 m; Spread 3 m. Bark gray, unremarkable. Leaves typical for the species, felty/scurvy surfaces; just starting to develop autumn leaf color (yellow banding). Fruit mostly green, occasional red, flatted drupes clustered at branch ends.
Collection Miscellaneous: Collected from 8 plants. Viburnum carlesii var carlesii only grows in coastal areas and Uleungo-do, in contrast to Viburnum carlesii var bitchiuense which is in mountainous/inland areas (as per Prof Sang-Hun Oh's current/ongoing research); if so, may need to revisit the extant 1977 Korean and later Chollipo collections that are growing at AA under V carlesii var bitchuense).
